  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Establish global standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and evidence\n- Extradition agreements\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align their legal frameworks\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering offenses\n- Similar enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International sanctions against countries with weak AML regulations\n- Economic consequences for non-compliance\n- Targeted financial restrictions\n\n6. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Cross-border communication networks\n- Real-time data exchange\n\n7. Technological Innovations\n- Digital tracking of financial transactions\n- Blockchain and cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced monitoring technologies\n\nThese intersections create a complex but interconnected global approach to combating money laundering.",
